{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T20:07:40.758030+00:00", "modified": "2025-02-06T23:42:19.330884+00:00", "id": 13538102, "conceptrecid": "13538101", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13538102", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13538101", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13538102", "metadata": {"title": "A formulated poly (I:C)/CCL21 as an effective mucosal adjuvant for gamma-irradiated influenza vaccine", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13538102", "publication_date": "2021", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) BACKGROUND: Several studies on gamma-irradiated influenza A virus (\u03b3-Flu) have revealed its superior efficacy for inducing homologous and heterologous virus-specific immunity. However, many inactivated vaccines, notably in nasal delivery, require adjuvants to increase the quality and magnitude of vaccine responses.\nMETHODS: To illustrate the impacts of co-administration of the gamma-irradiated H1N1 vaccine with poly (I:C) and recombinant murine CCL21, either alone or in combination with each other, as adjuvants on the vaccine potency, mice were inoculated intranasally 3 times at one-week interval with \u03b3-Flu alone or with any of the three adjuvant combinations and then challenged with a high lethal dose (10 LD50) of A/PR/8/34 (H1N1) influenza virus. Virus-specific humoral, mucosal, and cell-mediated immunity, as well as cytokine profiles in the spleen (IFN-\u03b3, IL-12, and IL-4), and in the lung homogenates (IL-6 and IL-10) were measured by ELISA. The proliferative response of restimulated splenocytes was also determined by MTT assay.\nRESULTS: The findings showed that the co-delivery of the \u03b3-Flu vaccine and CCL21 or Poly (I:C) significantly increased the vaccine immunogenicity compared to the non-adjuvanted vaccine, associated with more potent protection following challenge infection. However, the mice given a combination of CCL21 with poly (I:C) had strong antibody- and cell-mediated immunity, which were considerably higher than responses of mice receiving the \u03b3-Flu vaccine with each adjuvant separately. This combination also reduced inflammatory mediator levels (notably IL-10) in lung homogenate samples.\nCONCLUSIONS: The results indicate that adjuvantation with the CCL21 and poly (I:C) can successfully induce vigorous vaccine-mediated protection, suggesting a robust propensity for CCL21 plus poly (I:C) as a potent mucosal adjuvant.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Sabbaghi, Ailar", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Malek, Masoud", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Abdolahi, Sara", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Miri, Seyed Mohammad", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Alizadeh, Leila", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Samadi, Mehdi", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Mohebbi, Seyed Reza", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Ghaemi, Amir", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Adjuvants", "Adjuvants, Immunologic", "Administration, Intranasal", "Animals", "Antibodies, Viral", "CCL21", "Gamma-irradiated influenza vaccine", "Immunity, Cellular", "Immunity, Mucosal", "Influenza A Virus, H1N1 Subtype", "Influenza Vaccines", "Mice", "Mice, Inbred BALB C", "Orthomyxoviridae Infections", "Poly (I:C)", "Protective immunity", "Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/ad7d8228169286e4cbd2093c7d08c2fa", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/780c01688d30f345472954ba86e4a4be13c2d962b235a4bb7e87a15c32009c87", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/L3PMUDNN", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/L3PMUDNN", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/5c8a22db9cfc6b3598e1a790ca162b67!/b10327-12910", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/ce1e761